<subSubSection pageId="103" pageNumber="104" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="103.[151,1437,151,1365]" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,475,501]" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Johnson" authorityYear="2021" baseAuthorityName="Kusnezov" baseAuthorityYear="1951" box="[575,642,475,501]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pogonomyrmex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="103" pageNumber="104" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leonis">
<emphasis box="[575,642,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">leonis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, was named for Cañadón León, 
<collectingRegion box="[1002,1234,475,501]" country="Argentina" name="Santa Cruz" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">Santa Cruz Province</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1243,1357,475,501]" name="Argentina" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">Argentina</collectingCountry>
, where Kusnezov collected the 
<typeStatus box="[419,506,511,537]" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">syntype</typeStatus>
series. Cañadón León is now called Gobernador Gregores.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="103" pageNumber="104" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="103.[151,1437,151,1365]" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,332,546,572]" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">Discussion.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Johnson" authorityYear="2021" baseAuthorityName="Kusnezov" baseAuthorityYear="1951" box="[341,592,547,573]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pogonomyrmex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="103" pageNumber="104" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leonis">
<emphasis box="[341,592,547,573]" italics="true" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">Pogonomyrmex leonis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
likely co-occurs with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kusnezov. The" authorityYear="1953" box="[847,997,547,572]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pogonomyrmex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="103" pageNumber="104" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sanmartini">
<emphasis box="[847,997,547,572]" italics="true" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">P. sanmartini</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Snelling &amp; Hunt" baseAuthorityYear="1975" box="[1054,1228,547,573]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pogonomyrmex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="103" pageNumber="104" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vermiculatus">
<emphasis box="[1054,1228,547,573]" italics="true" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">P. vermiculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and possibly with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Johnson" authorityYear="2021" box="[151,284,583,609]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pogonomyrmex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="103" pageNumber="104" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="varicolor">
<emphasis box="[151,284,583,609]" italics="true" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">P. varicolor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kusnezov" authorityYear="1951" box="[348,518,583,609]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pogonomyrmex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="103" pageNumber="104" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="meridionalis">
<emphasis box="[348,518,583,609]" italics="true" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">P. meridionalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Johnson" authorityYear="2021" baseAuthorityName="Kusnezov" baseAuthorityYear="1951" box="[533,784,583,609]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pogonomyrmex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="103" pageNumber="104" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leonis">
<emphasis box="[533,784,583,609]" italics="true" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">Pogonomyrmex leonis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinguished from the first three species based on: (1) anterior portion of first gastral tergum moderately to strongly coriarious, rest of tergum smooth and shining, and (2) head ferruginous orange to orange-red; mesosoma, petiolar node, postpetiole blackish to black; gaster, legs orangish-brown to brownish-orange. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kusnezov. The" authorityYear="1953" box="[507,811,691,716]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pogonomyrmex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="103" pageNumber="104" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sanmartini">
<emphasis box="[507,811,691,716]" italics="true" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">Pogonomyrmex sanmartini</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Johnson" authorityYear="2021" box="[875,1007,691,717]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pogonomyrmex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="103" pageNumber="104" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="varicolor">
<emphasis box="[875,1007,691,717]" italics="true" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">P. varicolor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have striae on the first gastral tergum and/or a different color pattern. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Snelling &amp; Hunt" baseAuthorityYear="1975" box="[509,837,727,753]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pogonomyrmex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="103" pageNumber="104" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vermiculatus">
<emphasis box="[509,837,727,753]" italics="true" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">Pogonomyrmex vermiculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
usually has a smooth and shining first gastral tergum or occasionally with striae along the base of the segment, but the anterior portion of the first gastral tergum is never coriarious as occurs in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Johnson" authorityYear="2021" baseAuthorityName="Kusnezov" baseAuthorityYear="1951" box="[418,515,799,825]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pogonomyrmex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="103" pageNumber="104" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leonis">
<emphasis box="[418,515,799,825]" italics="true" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">P. leonis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Johnson" authorityYear="2021" baseAuthorityName="Kusnezov" baseAuthorityYear="1951" box="[531,783,799,825]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pogonomyrmex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="103" pageNumber="104" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leonis">
<emphasis box="[531,783,799,825]" italics="true" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">Pogonomyrmex leonis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is most similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kusnezov" authorityYear="1951" box="[1002,1174,799,825]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pogonomyrmex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="103" pageNumber="104" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="meridionalis">
<emphasis box="[1002,1174,799,825]" italics="true" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">P. meridionalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as both have a similar head shape and rugae patterning. However, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Johnson" authorityYear="2021" baseAuthorityName="Kusnezov" baseAuthorityYear="1951" box="[641,736,835,861]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pogonomyrmex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="103" pageNumber="104" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leonis">
<emphasis box="[641,736,835,861]" italics="true" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">P. leonis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs in having an orange-red head and black mesosoma and gaster, whereas 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kusnezov" authorityYear="1951" box="[333,504,871,897]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pogonomyrmex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="103" pageNumber="104" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="meridionalis">
<emphasis box="[333,504,871,897]" italics="true" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">P. meridionalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a black head and mesosoma and a dark orangish gaster. This species was not collected by the author such that it appears to be uncommon and/or it occurs less accessible areas of central southern 
<taxonomicName box="[151,265,943,969]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Patagonia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="103" pageNumber="170" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Patagonia</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="103.[151,1437,151,1365]" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Johnson" authorityYear="2021" baseAuthorityName="Kusnezov" baseAuthorityYear="1951" box="[199,450,979,1005]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pogonomyrmex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="103" pageNumber="104" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leonis">
<emphasis box="[199,450,979,1005]" italics="true" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">Pogonomyrmex leonis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<materialsCitation collectorName="Thus, I" country="Argentina" county="These" location="central Santa Cruz" municipality="The" pageId="103" pageNumber="104" specimenCount="1" specimenCount-worker="1" typeStatus="syntype">
is known only from the 
<typeStatus box="[732,819,979,1005]" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">syntype</typeStatus>
series of 
<specimenCount box="[931,1073,979,1005]" pageId="103" pageNumber="104" type="worker">five workers</specimenCount>
collected in 
<location LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:5027B677FFAFA479FF25FEA1FE786E59:DD5151BAFFADA479FB76FC55FA5F68E1" box="[1220,1432,979,1005]" country="Argentina" county="These" municipality="The" name="central Santa Cruz" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">central Santa Cruz</location>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[151,266,1015,1041]" name="Argentina" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">Argentina</collectingCountry>
. 
<collectingMunicipality box="[277,321,1015,1041]" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">The</collectingMunicipality>
range of variation in the species is unknown given the few workers that were collected in the type series, but several morphological characters make this a distinct taxon. 
<collectingCounty box="[968,1035,1051,1077]" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">These</collectingCounty>
characters include: (1) ferruginous orange to orange-red head and black mesosoma and gaster, (2)&gt; 12–15 weak, irregular, longitudinal rugae on the promesonotum that continue to the anterior margin of the pronotum, (3) long superior propodeal spines, and (4) first gastral tergum moderately to strongly coriarious over the basal area to the anterior one-third or more of segment. 
<collectorName box="[151,230,1195,1221]" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">Thus, I</collectorName>
elevate 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Johnson" authorityYear="2021" baseAuthorityName="Kusnezov" baseAuthorityYear="1951" box="[324,418,1195,1221]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pogonomyrmex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="103" pageNumber="104" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leonis">
<emphasis box="[324,418,1195,1221]" italics="true" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">P. leonis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from subspecies to rank as a valid species
</materialsCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="103" pageNumber="104" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="103.[151,1437,151,1365]" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,295,1230,1256]" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">Biology.</emphasis>
Nothing is known about the biology of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Johnson" authorityYear="2021" baseAuthorityName="Kusnezov" baseAuthorityYear="1951" box="[750,846,1231,1257]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pogonomyrmex" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="103" pageNumber="104" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leonis">
<emphasis box="[750,846,1231,1257]" italics="true" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">P. leonis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as it is only known from the 
<typeStatus box="[1181,1229,1231,1257]" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">type</typeStatus>
series, which was collected about 70 years ago. The 
<typeStatus box="[529,577,1267,1293]" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">type</typeStatus>
locality is likely at an elevation of 
<quantity box="[966,1093,1267,1293]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.5" metricValueMax="6.0" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="103" pageNumber="104" unit="m" value="450.0" valueMax="600.0" valueMin="300.0">300–600 m</quantity>
in the 
<taxonomicName authority="Steppe" authorityName="Steppe" box="[1167,1360,1267,1293]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Patagonia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="103" pageNumber="104" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Patagonia Steppe</taxonomicName>
ecoregion, as defined by 
<bibRefCitation author="Olson, D. M. &amp; Dinerstein, E. &amp; Wikramanayake, E. D. &amp; Burgess, N. D. &amp; Powell, G. V. N. &amp; Underwood, E. C. &amp; D'Amico, J. A. &amp; Itoua, I. &amp; Strand, H. E. &amp; Morrison, J. C. &amp; Loucks, C. J. &amp; Allnutt, T. F. &amp; Ricketts, T. H. &amp; Kura, Y. &amp; Lamoreux, J. F. &amp; Wettengel, W. W. &amp; Hedao, P. &amp; Kassem, K. R." box="[375,589,1303,1329]" pageId="103" pageNumber="104" pagination="933 - 938" refId="ref148173" refString="Olson, D. M., Dinerstein, E., Wikramanayake, E. D., Burgess, N. D., Powell, G. V. N., Underwood, E. C., D'Amico, J. A., Itoua, I., Strand, H. E., Morrison, J. C., Loucks, C. J., Allnutt, T. F., Ricketts, T. H., Kura, Y., Lamoreux, J. F., Wettengel, W. W., Hedao, P. &amp; Kassem, K. R. (2001) Terrestrial ecoregions of the world: a new map of life on Earth. Bioscience, 51 (11), 933 - 938. https: // doi. org / 10.1641 / 0006 - 3568 (2001) 051 [0933: TEOTWA] 2.0. CO; 2" type="journal article" year="2001">
Olson 
<emphasis box="[450,500,1303,1329]" italics="true" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">et al</emphasis>
. (2001)
</bibRefCitation>
(
<figureCitation box="[605,738,1303,1329]" captionStart="FIGURE 43" captionStartId="94.[151,250,1927,1951]" captionTargetBox="[420,1165,181,1903]" captionTargetId="figure-19@94.[420,1167,181,1903]" captionTargetPageId="94" captionText="FIGURE 43. Geographic distribution of: (A) Pogonomyrmex intermedia, (B) P. lagunabravensis, and (C) P. leonis. The large black circle in each panel denotes the type locality." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5499251" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5499251/files/figure.png" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">Figure 43C</figureCitation>
). This species most likely inhabits the vast, difficult to access central areas of 
<taxonomicName box="[329,443,1339,1365]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Patagonia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="103" pageNumber="170" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Patagonia</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
